{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17505639","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17505639"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:33:35+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:33:35+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2462"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2462","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2462"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.28,0.08,0.5,0.1]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2462"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115068"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2462","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2462"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2462"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97076"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"36"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"112"},{"type":"tags","id":"1165"},{"type":"tags","id":"1536"},{"type":"tags","id":"2066"},{"type":"tags","id":"3764"},{"type":"tags","id":"4969"},{"type":"tags","id":"4970"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2038"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3496"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3863"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3876"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19318"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38623"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44639"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44780"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115068","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/115068"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 69-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a four-month history of increasing lower back pain. Over the last three years, he has experienced troubles with urination, including increased frequency, hesitancy, and dribbling after micturition. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. His abdomen is soft and there is no suprapubic dullness. Digital rectal examination reveals a firm enlarged prostate with loss of the median sulcus and several firm nodules. His prostate-specific antigen level is 18 ng/mL (2.0-5.6). A CT scan shows several enlarged retroperitoneal and pelvic lymph nodes, with scattered sclerotic lesions in the lumbar spine.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management for symptom relief?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Orchidectomy","Androgen deprivation therapy","Regular paracetamol","Radiotherapy","Bisphosphonate"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with metastatic prostate cancer, evidenced by an elevated prostate-specific antigen, abnormal digital rectal examination, and imaging showing lymphadenopathy and sclerotic bone lesions. For relief of localised bone pain, \u003Cstrong\u003Eradiotherapy\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate choice. It provides the most rapid symptom relief, with 50% of responders showing benefit within one to two weeks. Even a single targeted fraction can significantly reduce pain.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAndrogen deprivation therapy\u003C/strong\u003E is indeed indicated for metastatic prostate cancer and will provide long-term benefits, including reducing the risk of ureteric compression from nodal disease and urinary retention from local disease progression. However, it will not provide rapid pain relief and may actually cause initial pain flares.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOrchidectomy\u003C/strong\u003E is a surgical form of androgen deprivation that some patients prefer to avoid long-term medication. However, like medical androgen deprivation, it will not provide immediate pain relief.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERegular paracetamol\u003C/strong\u003E alone is inadequate for managing bone pain from metastatic disease and does not address the underlying cause.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBisphosphonate\u003C/strong\u003E therapy is primarily used for hypercalcaemia from lytic bone lesions. While it may help with diffuse bone pain or recurrent pain in previously irradiated areas, it is not first-line for localised bone pain.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Radiotherapy is the treatment of choice for rapid relief of localised bone pain associated with metastatic cancer.","Androgen deprivation therapy is indicated for metastatic prostate cancer but may cause initial pain flares.","Prostate cancer commonly presents with lower urinary tract symptoms and bone metastases typically cause sclerotic lesions."],"references":["Macedo F, Ladeira K, Pinho F, Saraiva N, Bonito N, et al. Bone Metastases: An Overview. Oncol Rev. 2017;11(1):321. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC5444408/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97076"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2462"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97076","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/97076"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-22T09:14:53+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-22T09:14:53+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2462"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115068"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"31","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/31"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf97","name":"Oncology","synonyms":[],"des